Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue on .NET 8 |
|----------|---------|-----------------|
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable |
| `_thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement fallback | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `while (true)` in `RunLoop` | Cancellable work loop | No way to stop cooperatively |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call | Not cancellation-aware |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wakes on either a new event OR cancellation
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (signaled == 1) // token.WaitHandle fired → shutting down
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes pre-existing bug where
            // multiple Enqueue calls between processing cycles lost signals)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait up to 5s for clean exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` | `Interrupt` is obsolete; token signals `WaitAny` cleanly |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed entirely | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative exit — thread checks the token each iteration |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` leak if not disposed |

## Key Pitfalls

1. **`WaitOne` → `WaitAny`** — If you only replace `Abort`/`Interrupt` with `Cancel()` but leave `WaitOne()`, the thread stays blocked forever because `WaitOne` doesn't observe the token.

2. **Drain the queue** — The original code dequeued one item per signal. If `Enqueue` is called twice before `RunLoop` wakes, the second item's `Set()` is lost (event is already set). The inner `while` loop drains all pending items.

3. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Always wrap the owner in `IDisposable`.

4. **Cancellation is cooperative, not instant** — If `Handle(item)` runs for 30 seconds, `Stop()` won't return until it finishes (or the 5s `Join` timeout expires). If `Handle` is long-running, pass the token into it and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints.

5. **`Join` timeout no longer has a fallback** — The old code called `Abort()` after `Join(5000)`. In .NET 8 there is no forcible kill for a managed thread. If `Handle` can hang, move that work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`, or redesign `Handle` to be cancellation-aware.
